0","1223–Male":"1223–Deceased","about 1271":"about 1271","Aft 1286":"after 1286","1286":"1286","1340":"1340","1296":"1296","1250":"1250","1271":"1271","1280":"1280","1305":"1305","1326":"1326","Abt 1250":"about 1250","1223":"1223","1278":"1278","1255":"1255","ABT 1278":"about 1278","1265":"1265","ABT 1280":"about 1280","Great Bealings, Suffolk, England":"Great Bealings, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom","Swaffham Prior, Cambridgeshire, England":"Swaffham Prior, Cambridgeshire, England","England":"England, United Kingdom","Thurning, Woodhurst, Huntingdonshire, England":"Thurning, Huntingdonshire, England, United Kingdom","Wormleighton, Warwickshire, England":"Wormleighton, Warwickshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Moyne","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["1  Norman, English: nickname from Old French  <i>moine</i>, Anglo-Norman French  <i>muine</i>,  <i>moingne</i> ‘monk’. Some of the following early bearers without the definite article could alternatively belong with (2).","2  English:  see  Moon   (1)."],"variants":[{"name":"Moin","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): variant of <b>Moyne</b>, a nickname from Old French <i>moine</i>, Anglo-Norman French <i>muine</i>, <i>moingne</i> ‘monk’.","Muslim (mainly the Indian subcontinent): unexplained."]},{"name":"Moon","meanings":["Irish: variant of   Mohan  .","English (of Norman origin): habitational name from Moyon in La Manche. Compare   Mounce  .","Americanized form of German   Mohn   or of some other similar (like-sounding) surname."]},{"name":"Moynan","meanings":["Irish: perhaps a diminutive of   Moyne   or a reduced form of   Moynihan  ."]},{"name":"Moine","meanings":["French: from <i>moine</i> ‘monk’, probably applied as an occupational name for a servant at a monastery or an ironic nickname for someone of monkish behavior or appearance. Compare   Lemoine  ."]},{"name":"Moynes","meanings":["English: variant of   Moyne   with post-medieval excrescent  <i>-s</i>."]}]},{"name":"Margaret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Margaret Moyne was born about 1250, in Thurning, Huntingdonshire, England, United Kingdom as the daughter of Berenger le Moyne. She had at least 2 sons and 1 daughter with John Pêche. She died after 1286, in England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"Abt 1250–Aft 1286":"umbes 1250–pärast 1286","1250–1286":"1250–1286","1265–1326":"1265–1326","1255–1296":"1255–1296","1271–1305":"1271–1305","1278–Male":"1278–Surnud","1280–1340":"1280–1340","1223–Male":"1223–Surnud","about 1271":"umbes 1271","Aft 1286":"pärast 1286","1286":"1286","1340":"1340","1296":"1296","1250":"1250","1271":"1271","1280":"1280","1305":"1305","1326":"1326","Abt 1250":"umbes 1250","1223":"1223","1278":"1278","1255":"1255","ABT 1278":"umbes 1278","1265":"1265","ABT 1280":"umbes 1280","Great Bealings, Suffolk, England":"Great Bealings, Suffolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Swaffham Prior, Cambridgeshire, England":"Swaffham Prior, Cambridgeshire, England","England":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Thurning, Woodhurst, Huntingdonshire, England":"Thurning, Huntingdonshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Wormleighton, Warwickshire, England":"Wormleighton, Warwickshire, England"},"fi":{"Abt 1250–Aft 1286":"noin 1250–1286 jälkeen","1250–1286":"1250–1286","1265–1326":"1265–1326","1255–1296":"1255–1296","1271–1305":"1271–1305","1278–Male":"1278–Kuollut","1280–1340":"1280–1340","1223–Male":"1223–Kuollut","about 1271":"noin 1271","Aft 1286":"1286 jälkeen","1286":"1286","1340":"1340","1296":"1296","1250":"1250","1271":"1271","1280":"1280","1305":"1305","1326":"1326","Abt 1250":"noin 1250","1223":"1223","1278":"1278","1255":"1255","ABT 1278":"noin 